# Plan on premium model, implement on Auto (hard rule)

When the operator uses a **premium / thinking model** (for example Opus
4.8) for **design and planning**, then asks for **Auto** (or an
equivalent cheap execution tier) to **implement** an approved plan, the
orchestrator must **honor that split**. Carrying the planning model
forward into implementation subagents is a **cost and scope violation**,
not a helpful default.

## The rule

> **Planning model ≠ implementation model.** If the operator says
> implementation runs in **Auto** (or names a cheap/fast execution
> model), every implementation path — direct edits, background subagents
> (`Task`), and parallel agents — must use **Auto** unless the operator
> explicitly names a different model for that implementation step.
> The model used to write the plan does not authorize upgrading
> implementers.**

## Required behavior

1. **Recognize the two phases.**
   - **Planning phase:** architecture, mockups, `docs/dev/*.md` plans,
     trade-offs, sequential specs, test matrices. May use Opus or
     another premium model when the operator chose it.
   - **Implementation phase:** execute an **already-written** plan
     phase-by-phase in code. Defaults to **Auto** when the operator
     says "Auto mode", "run in Auto", or equivalent.

2. **Launching subagents (`Task` tool).**
   - When the operator requested **Auto** for implementers: **omit**
     the `model` parameter (Cursor Auto routing) **or** pass an explicit
     cheap slug the operator named (for example `composer-2.5-fast`).
   - **Do not** pass `claude-opus-4-8-thinking-high`, `claude-opus-4-8`,
     or any other premium/thinking slug unless the operator **explicitly**
     asked for that model on **this implementation step**.

3. **Before launching parallel implementers**, state one line to the
   operator confirming model tier, for example:
   `Launching 2 Auto implementers from the Win32/Tauri plans (no Opus override).`

4. **Parent context does not upgrade children.** If this conversation
   used Opus for planning, that fact **must not** appear as a reason to
   pick Opus for `Task`, "complexity", or "complete all phases".

## Forbidden

- Passing `model: claude-opus-4-8-thinking-high` (or any Opus/thinking
  slug) on `Task` when the operator said implementation runs in **Auto**.
- Justifying an Opus implementer with "the plan was written in Opus",
  "multi-phase", or "complete all phases automatically" without an
  explicit operator request to use Opus for **implementation**.
- Silently substituting a premium model because the task "looks hard".
- Re-launching the same implementer on a premium model after Auto was
  requested, without asking first.

## Allowed exceptions (operator must say so explicitly)

- Operator names a specific model for implementers: *"Implement Phase 2
  with Opus"* or *"Use GPT-5 Codex for the Win32 track."*
- Operator says to use the **same model as this chat** for
  implementation (rare; must be literal, not inferred).

## Worked violation → fix

**Violation** (2026-06-13 elevation redesign session):

```text
User: "Create two agents … both run in Auto mode … Complete all phases."
Assistant: Task(..., model: "claude-opus-4-8-thinking-high", ...)
```

**Fix:**

```text
User: "Create two agents … both run in Auto mode … Complete all phases."
Assistant: Task(..., /* no model field — Auto */ prompt: "Implement Phases 0–5 per plan …")
Assistant: Task(..., /* no model field — Auto */ prompt: "Implement Phases 1–5 per plan …")
```

If the operator later wants a premium model on a stuck slice, they ask
once for that slice only; the orchestrator does not pre-upgrade.

